# delegate: let a Dagger coding agent hand a self-contained subtask to a fresh
# sub-agent and get back only the distilled result.
#
# The motivating case (from a real session retro): a noisy, context-heavy loop
# — "build the CLI, boot the engine, run the agent, poke the TUI, report just
# the final screen and whether it panicked" — dumps thousands of lines of build
# and boot output into the parent's context for two useful bits of signal. A
# sub-agent absorbs all that: it runs the loop in ITS OWN conversation (rolled
# up under this tool call in the TUI, see the conversation nesting in
# dagql/dagui/conversation.go) and hands back a single concise report.
#
# Modeled on ./modules/tui-qa (the @agent-tools shape). The sub-agent is a fresh
# root `llm` conversation (Query.llm — inherits the session's default model and
# auth) bound to the same Workspace as the parent (auto-filled; see
# core/llm_object_tools.go), so it has the same tools. It runs to completion via
# `loop` and we surface its `lastReply`.
#
# Scope: this is for investigative / QA / analysis legwork that reports back in
# text. The sub-agent's own workspace edits are NOT merged into yours (the tool
# returns a String, not a Changeset) — delegate the looking, not the editing.
"""
Offload a self-contained subtask to a fresh sub-agent and get back only its
final report.
"""
type Delegate {
  """
  Compose the delegate tool onto a base LLM.
  """
  agent(base: LLM!): LLM! @agent {
    base
      .withTools(currentNode)
      .withSystemPrompt(systemPrompt)
  }

  """
  Delegate a self-contained subtask to a fresh sub-agent and return only its
  final answer.

  The sub-agent starts a brand-new conversation bound to your workspace (so it
  has the same tools you do), works the task autonomously to completion, and
  hands back a single concise result — all of its intermediate tool calls and
  chatter stay in the sub-agent's own context (rolled up under this call)
  instead of flooding yours. Reach for it to offload noisy, context-heavy, or
  well-scoped legwork — e.g. "build and run the agent, drive the TUI, and report
  just the final screen and whether it panicked" — and keep your own context
  focused. Note: the sub-agent's own workspace edits are not merged back, so use
  this for investigation/QA/analysis, not for making edits.
  """
  delegate(
    """
    The subtask for the sub-agent. Be specific about what to do AND exactly what
    to report back, since only its final reply returns to you.
    """
    task: String!,
    source: Workspace!,
    """
    Cap the sub-agent's steps so a runaway task can't loop forever. The call
    fails if the cap is hit before the sub-agent finishes.
    """
    maxSteps: Int! = 40,
  ): String! {
    source
      .agents
      .compose(llm)
      .withWorkspace(source)
      .withSystemPrompt(subAgentPrompt)
      .withPrompt(task)
      .loop(maxSteps: maxSteps)
      .lastReply
  }

  # Instructions for the PARENT agent holding this tool.
  let systemPrompt: String! = """
    You can hand a self-contained subtask to a fresh sub-agent with the
    `delegate` tool. The sub-agent runs in its own conversation with the same
    tools you have and returns only its final report, so its intermediate work
    never enters your context.

    Delegate when a subtask is noisy (dumps a lot of output), context-heavy, or
    cleanly scoped — e.g. reproducing a bug end-to-end, exploring an unfamiliar
    subtree, or running a build/QA loop — and phrase the task so it says both
    what to do and exactly what to report back. Keep doing the work yourself
    when it's small, needs your accumulated context, or must edit files (a
    sub-agent's edits are not merged back to your workspace).
  """

  # Instructions for the SUB-agent spawned by `delegate`.
  let subAgentPrompt: String! = """
    You are a sub-agent handling one self-contained task for another agent.
    Work autonomously to completion using the available tools — do not ask
    follow-up questions. When done, reply with a single concise report covering
    exactly what was asked and nothing more: the outcome, the key evidence
    (relevant output, not raw dumps), and any errors, panics, or surprises.
    Your reply is the ONLY thing that returns to the caller, so make it
    self-contained.
  """
}
